00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:13.810
Israel Abrams, a scholar at
Cambridge University writing

00:11:13.810 --> 00:11:17.850
in the 1890s, like many
other Jewish intellectuals

00:11:17.850 --> 00:11:23.600
of his time, saw in the study of
history a way to defend the Jews

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:26.070
against scurrilous attacks.

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:31.310
In 1896 in his probably
most famous book,

00:11:31.310 --> 00:11:35.520
Jewish Life in the Middle
Ages, in a chapter on trades

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:39.290
and occupations, he directly
challenged the French writer

00:11:39.290 --> 00:11:45.090
[inaudible] who the year
before in his book had asserted

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:47.800
that Jews were cowards.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:50.210
You know, there's
an air quote there.

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:52.730
They were cowards
because they, quote,

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:57.740
"shunned arduous physical
undertakings and were averse

00:11:57.740 --> 00:12:01.450
to dangerous occupations."

00:12:01.450 --> 00:12:07.760
Abrams countered this
directly, and in his words,

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:12.360
the Jewish peddler of recent
centuries was no coward.

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:17.640
Had he lacked courage, he
must have remained at home.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:21.060
We're going to use Abrams
words as a way to --

00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:25.850
as a point of entry to thinking
about the historic significant

00:12:25.850 --> 00:12:31.540
of peddling and its connection
to the transformative phenomenon

00:12:31.540 --> 00:12:35.900
of Jewish migrations
in the modern period.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:39.750
Going out on the road laden
with a jumble of goods,

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:43.370
sometimes specializing in
a particular type of wear,

00:12:43.370 --> 00:12:45.900
was a profound binding

00:12:45.900 --> 00:12:49.540
and nearly universal
Jewish experience in the --

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:53.160
what we now, as historians,
call the long 19th century,

00:12:53.160 --> 00:12:55.310
starting in the late
18th century

00:12:55.310 --> 00:12:59.020
and going into the 1920s.

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:02.930
Not that all Jews peddled,
but rather so many did

00:13:02.930 --> 00:13:05.270
in the modern history
of the Jewish people

00:13:05.270 --> 00:13:08.090
that it provided the
central pivotal --

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:10.520
that it played a
central pivotal role

00:13:10.520 --> 00:13:14.230
in shaping new Jewish
communities.

00:13:14.230 --> 00:13:16.390
Jewish migrations
out of familiar

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:20.210
but economically declining
regions to new lands wide open

00:13:20.210 --> 00:13:23.210
for settlement and
business, opened up because

00:13:23.210 --> 00:13:27.680
of colonial expansion and
the spread of capitalism,

00:13:27.680 --> 00:13:34.470
made it possible for Jewish
peddlers to take to the road.

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:40.170
Peddlers very ordinary
prosaic, peripatetic figures,

00:13:40.170 --> 00:13:42.960
who unfortunately left
us very little in the way

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:46.240
of a paper trail,
served as the juggernauts

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:50.330
for the Jewish migration,
Jewish migrations.

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:53.480
Their experiences on the
road as the human engines

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:57.200
that drove the massive Jewish
population shift, which brought

00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:00.680
over four-and-a-half
million Jews out of central

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:05.740
and eastern Europe as well
as the Ottoman Empire,

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:11.360
to new lands, deserves to be
thought of in historical --

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:13.450
in a historical context.

